csv_file_path = "/content/RAW_recipes.csv"

from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DoubleType

schema = StructType([
    StructField("name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("id", StringType(), True),

In[14]:
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession, Row
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType

spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("RecipeRDDParsing").getOrCreate()

data_rdd = spark.sparkContext.textFile("/content/RAW_recipes.csv")

header = data_rdd.first()
data_rdd_noheader = data_rdd.filter(lambda row: row != header)

schema = StructType([
    StructField("name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("minutes", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("contributor_id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("submitted", StringType(), True),
    StructField("tags", StringType(), True),
    StructField("nutrition", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_steps", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("steps", StringType(), True),
    StructField("description", StringType(), True),
    StructField("ingredients", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_ingredients", IntegerType(), True)
])

def parse_recipe(line):
    parts = line.split(';')
    if len(parts) == 12:
        return (
            parts[0].strip('"'),
            parts[1].strip('"'),
            int(parts[2]) if parts[2].isdigit() else None,
            parts[3].strip('"'),
            parts[4].strip('"'),
            parts[5].strip('"'),
            parts[6].strip('"'),
            int(parts[7]) if parts[7].isdigit() else None,
            parts[8].strip('"'),
            parts[9].strip('"'),
            parts[10].strip('"'),
            int(parts[11]) if parts[11].isdigit() else None
        )
    else:
        return None

parsed_rdd = data_rdd_noheader.map(parse_recipe).filter(lambda x: x is not None)

recipes_df = spark.createDataFrame(parsed_rdd, schema=schema)

recipes_df.show(5, truncate=False)
recipes_df.printSchema()

spark.stop()

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType

spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("RecipeAnalysis").getOrCreate()

schema = StructType([
    StructField("name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("minutes", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("contributor_id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("submitted", StringType(), True),
    StructField("tags", StringType(), True),
    StructField("nutrition", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_steps", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("steps", StringType(), True),
    StructField("description", StringType(), True),
    StructField("ingredients", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_ingredients", IntegerType(), True)
])

csv_path = "/content/RAW_recipes.csv"

recipes_df = spark.read.csv(csv_path, schema=schema, header=True, sep=';')

recipes_df.show(5, truncate=False)
recipes_df.printSchema()

# Step 6: GroupBy and Aggregations

# 1. Count number of recipes by each 'minutes' value
print("Count of recipes by minutes:")
recipes_df.groupBy("minutes").count().show()

# 2. Count recipes by each contributor and display top 10
print("Top 10 contributors by recipe count:")
recipes_df.groupBy("contributor_id").count().orderBy("count", ascending=False).show(10, truncate=60)

# 3. Filter recipes with 'minutes' >= 60 (long/complex recipes)
print("Recipes with minutes >= 60:")
long_recipes = recipes_df.filter(recipes_df.minutes >= 60)
long_recipes.show(10, truncate=80)

spark.stop()

from pyspark.sql.functions import substring

Convert Log Messages into Features (TF-IDF)

In[25]:
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, when
from pyspark.ml.feature import Tokenizer, StopWordsRemover, HashingTF, IDF
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline

spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("RecipeTextProcessing").getOrCreate()

df = recipes_df.withColumn("text_col", when(col("description").isNull(), "").otherwise(col("description").cast("string")))

tokenizer = Tokenizer(inputCol="text_col", outputCol="words")
remover = StopWordsRemover(inputCol="words", outputCol="filtered")
hashingTF = HashingTF(inputCol="filtered", outputCol="rawFeatures", numFeatures=2000)
idf = IDF(inputCol="rawFeatures", outputCol="features")

pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[tokenizer, remover, hashingTF, idf])

# Fit pipeline model and transform data
model = pipeline.fit(df)
feature_df = model.transform(df)

# Show original text and extracted features
feature_df.select("text_col", "features").show(5, truncate=80)

# Stop Spark session when done (optional)
# spark.stop()

Applying KMeans Clustering on Log Messages

In[28]:
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler
from pyspark.ml.clustering import KMeans
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DoubleType

spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("KMeansExample").getOrCreate()

# Define the schema to ensure correct data types
schema = StructType([
    StructField("name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("minutes", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("contributor_id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("submitted", StringType(), True),
    StructField("tags", StringType(), True),
    StructField("nutrition", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_steps", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("steps", StringType(), True),
    StructField("description", StringType(), True),
    StructField("ingredients", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_ingredients", IntegerType(), True),
])

# Load the data using the predefined schema
df = spark.read.csv("/content/RAW_recipes.csv", header=True, schema=schema, multiLine=True, escape="\"")

feature_columns = ["minutes", "n_steps", "n_ingredients"]
df = df.dropna(subset=feature_columns)

assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=feature_columns, outputCol="features")
feature_df = assembler.transform(df)

# Ensure k is not larger than the number of distinct data points
distinct_points = feature_df.select("features").distinct().count()
k = min(5, distinct_points)

# Train KMeans
kmeans = KMeans(k=k, seed=1, featuresCol="features")
model = kmeans.fit(feature_df)

# Predict clusters
clusters = model.transform(feature_df)

# Show the name column and cluster predictions
clusters.select("name", "prediction").show(10, truncate=80)

spark.stop()

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, when
from pyspark.ml.feature import Tokenizer, StopWordsRemover, HashingTF, IDF
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.ml.clustering import KMeans
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DoubleType

# Start Spark session
spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("RecipeCluster").getOrCreate()

# Define the schema to ensure correct data types
schema = StructType([
    StructField("name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("minutes", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("contributor_id", StringType(), True),
    StructField("submitted", StringType(), True),
    StructField("tags", StringType(), True),
    StructField("nutrition", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_steps", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("steps", StringType(), True),
    StructField("description", StringType(), True),
    StructField("ingredients", StringType(), True),
    StructField("n_ingredients", IntegerType(), True),
])

# Load the data directly into a Spark DataFrame
df = spark.read.csv("/content/RAW_recipes.csv", header=True, schema=schema, multiLine=True, escape="\"")

# Pick a text column for NLP clustering
# Use "name", "description", or any other string/text column
column_to_process = "name"  # Change to "description" if more relevant

# Ensure column is cast to string and handle nulls
df = df.withColumn("string_col", when(col(column_to_process).isNull(), "").otherwise(col(column_to_process).cast("string")))

# NLP pipeline: Tokenizer, StopWordsRemover, HashingTF, IDF
tokenizer = Tokenizer(inputCol="string_col", outputCol="words")
remover = StopWordsRemover(inputCol="words", outputCol="filtered")
hashingTF = HashingTF(inputCol="filtered", outputCol="rawFeatures", numFeatures=2000)
idf = IDF(inputCol="rawFeatures", outputCol="features")
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[tokenizer, remover, hashingTF, idf])

feature_model = pipeline.fit(df)
feature_df = feature_model.transform(df)

# Ensure k is not larger than the number of distinct data points
distinct_points = feature_df.select("features").distinct().count()
k = min(5, distinct_points)

# Train KMeans, adjust k to the dataset size if needed
kmeans = KMeans(k=k, seed=1, featuresCol="features")
model = kmeans.fit(feature_df)
clusters = model.transform(feature_df)

# Show group counts per cluster
clusters.groupBy("prediction").count().orderBy("count", ascending=False).show()

# Stop Spark session when done (optional)

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Collect features and cluster assignments to Pandas
data = clusters.select("features", "prediction").toPandas()
X = data['features'].tolist()
y = data['prediction']

# Convert SparseVector to array
import numpy as np
X_arr = np.array([x.toArray() for x in X])

silhouette_vals = silhouette_samples(X_arr, y)

# Plot silhouette scores by cluster
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
y_ticks = []
y_lower = 10

for i in range(k):  # k is number of clusters
    ith_cluster_silhouette_values = silhouette_vals[y == i]
    ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()
    size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
    y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

    plt.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                      0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                      alpha=0.7)
    plt.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))
    y_lower = y_upper + 10

plt.xlabel("Silhouette coefficient values")
plt.ylabel("Cluster label")
plt.title("Silhouette plot for the clusters")
plt.show()

In[46]:
import seaborn as sns
from collections import Counter

# Collect text for each cluster
cluster_texts = {}
for i in range(k):
    texts = clusters.filter(clusters.prediction == i).select("string_col").rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()
    cluster_texts[i] = ' '.join(texts).split()

# Calculate frequency of top 10 words in each cluster
top_words = set()
freq_dfs = []

for i, words in cluster_texts.items():
    counter = Counter(words)
    common_words = dict(counter.most_common(10))
    top_words.update(common_words.keys())
    freq_dfs.append(common_words)

# Create DataFrame for heatmap
import pandas as pd
heatmap_df = pd.DataFrame(index=range(k), columns=list(top_words)).fillna(0)

for i, freq in enumerate(freq_dfs):
    for word, count in freq.items():
        heatmap_df.at[i, word] = count

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.heatmap(heatmap_df, annot=True, fmt='g', cmap='YlGnBu')
plt.xlabel('Words')
plt.ylabel('Cluster')
plt.title('Top Word Frequencies per Cluster')
plt.show()
